A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of an aldehydic acid.
Any organooxygen compound that has the general formula RC(OR(1))(OR(2))(OR(3)), where R(1), R(2), R(3) =/= H.
A 3-sn-phosphatidyl-L-serine(1-) in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 34 carbons in total and 0 double bonds.

Any toxin secreted by bacteria, viruses, fungi or protozoa enabling them to achieve colonisation of a niche in the host, inhibit or evade the host's immune response, enter and exit cells, or obtain nutrition from the host.
A lysophosphatidylethanolamine zwitterion in which the remaining acyl group (position not specified) contains 16 carbons and 0 double bonds.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 38 with 1 double bond.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 42 with 2 double bonds.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 44 with 1 double bond.
A sphingomyelin in which the total number of carbons in the sphingoid base and fatty acyl groups is 44 with 2 double bonds.

Any organic molecular entity whose stucture is based on derivatives of a phenyl-substituted 1-phenylpropane possessing a C15 or C16 skeleton, or such a structure which is condensed with a C6-C3 lignan precursors. The term is a 'superclass' comprising all members of the classes of flavonoid, isoflavonoid, neoflavonoid, chalcones, dihydrochalcones, aurones, pterocarpan, coumestans, rotenoid, flavonolignan, homoflavonoid and flavonoid oligomers. Originally restricted to natural products, the term is also applied to synthetic compounds related to them.
Any chromenochromene resulting from the formal cis-fusion of two dihydro chromene rings, together with their substituted derivatives.
Members of the class of rotenoid which consists of a 6a,12a-dihydrochromeno[3,4-b]chromen-12(6H)-one skeleton and its substituted products.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a natural product by partial chemical synthesis.
A cyclic ketal in which the ketal carbon is the only common atom of two rings.
A HODE that consists of (10E,12Z)-octadecadienoic acid with the hydroxy substituent located at position 9.
Any molecule that consists of at least one carbon atom as part of the electrically neutral entity.
An agonist that binds to and activates aryl hydrocarbon receptors (AhRs).
A biomacromolecule composed of carbohydrate residues which is secreted by a microorganism into the surrounding environment.
A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of any glycerophosphoethanolamine.
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl).
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as octadecanoyl (stearoyl).
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as eicosanoyl.
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as tetracosanoyl.
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as docosanoyl.
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexacosanoyl.
An N-acylglycine that is glycine with an amine hydrogen substituted by a 2-methylbut-2-enoyl (tiglyl) group.

Any organic amino compound that has an amino group and a hydroxy group attached to the same carbon atom. Hemiaminals are intermediates in the formation of imines by addition of an amine to an aldehyde or ketone; those derived from primary amines are particularly unstable.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of GM1 ganglioside.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid that contains three double bonds.
An  EC 1.11.1.* (peroxidases) inhibitor that inhibits the action of L-ascorbate peroxidase (EC 1.11.1.11).

label.value: EC 3.6.* (hydrolases acting on acid anhydrides) inhibitor

definition.value: Any hydrolase inhibitor that interferes with the action of a hydrolase which acts on acid anhydrides (EC 3.6.*.*).
An agonist at any adenosine receptor.
An acaricide that kills mites of the genus Sarcoptes.
A drug used in treating and healing of wounds.
A mancude heterobicyclic organic group consisting of a benzene ring fused to a pyrrole ring.
Any organic molecule containing a C#C bond.
Any naphthyridine derivative that is a derivative of 1,8-naphthyridine.
Any organonitrogen heterocyclic compound that is a derivative of a naphthyridine.
A bicyclic organic group that contains both carbon and hetero atoms.

A vitamin D that is calciol or its hydroxylated metabolites calcidiol and calcitriol. Calciol (also known as vitamin D3) acts as a hormone precursor, being hydroxylated in the liver to calcidiol (25-hydroxyvitamin D3), which is then further hydroxylated in the kidney to give calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3), the active hormone.
